"'''''Racaille'''''" and its ''[[verlan]]'' form "'''''caillera'''''" is a [[French language|French]] [[Pejorative|derogatory term]] that roughly means ''rabble'' (although some translate it as ''riff-raff'' or ''dregs'') and has been specifically associated in [[France]] since the [[nineties]] with some young residents (minor offenders in particular) of the poor ''[[banlieue]]s'' or ''cités''. It is widely used to name their culture, and particularly their clothing style (see ''[[chav]]''). It gained international notoriety when used by French interior minister, [[Nicolas Sarkozy]], to describe the residents of crime-ridden neighborhoods. 


